---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
---

<Base title="Pain Reprocessing Therapy (PRT)">
  <article class="container page-section">
    <h1>Pain Reprocessing Therapy (PRT)</h1>
    <p style="color: var(--text-muted); font-size: 1rem; max-width: 650px;">
      A step-by-step protocol developed by Alan Gordon, LCSW. PRT retrains the brain to
      reinterpret pain signals as safe — breaking the chronic pain cycle at its source.
    </p>

    <div class="card" style="margin: 1.5rem 0; background: linear-gradient(135deg, var(--teal-light), #F0FDFA); border-color: var(--teal);">
      <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 1.05rem;">
        <strong>Research:</strong> RCT in JAMA Psychiatry (2021) — 66% pain-free after 4 weeks,
        98% improved. Results maintained at 5-year follow-up.
        <a href="https://jamanetwork.com/journals/jamapsychiatry/fullarticle/2784694" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
          Read the study →
        </a>
      </p>
    </div>

    <h2>The Five Components of PRT</h2>

    <section style="margin: 2rem 0;">
      <div style="display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 0.75rem; margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">
        <div style="background: var(--teal); color: white; border-radius: 50%; width: 36px; height: 36px; display: flex; align-items: center; justify-content: center; font-weight: 700;">1</div>
        <h3 style="margin: 0;">Education: Understanding the brain origins of pain</h3>
      </div>
      <p>
        The first step is cognitive: learn why your pain persists. Understanding that chronic
        pain can be generated by the brain — not by tissue damage — is itself therapeutic
        (<strong>Pain Neuroscience Education</strong>). Key concepts to internalize:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>Pain is a danger signal produced by the brain, not a direct readout of body damage</li>
        <li>The brain can learn to generate pain even when tissues are healthy</li>
        <li>Neuroplasticity means the brain can change — both to learn and unlearn pain</li>
        <li>Your pain is 100% real — you're not "making it up"</li>
        <li>Understanding this reduces fear, which is the first step to recovery</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section style="margin: 2rem 0;">
      <div style="display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 0.75rem; margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">
        <div style="background: var(--teal); color: white; border-radius: 50%; width: 36px; height: 36px; display: flex; align-items: center; justify-content: center; font-weight: 700;">2</div>
        <h3 style="margin: 0;">Gathering personalized evidence</h3>
      </div>
      <p>
        Build genuine conviction that <em>your</em> pain is neuroplastic. Generic knowledge
        isn't enough — you need to see the pattern in your own life. Collect evidence:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>Did your pain begin during a period of stress?</li>
        <li>Does pain move or spread unpredictably?</li>
        <li>Are symptoms inconsistent — good days and bad days?</li>
        <li>Do you have multiple symptoms in different body systems?</li>
        <li>Have structural treatments (surgery, injections, PT) not helped?</li>
        <li>Does stress make it worse? Do enjoyable activities make it better?</li>
        <li>What were your childhood experiences? Any adversity or pressure?</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        <strong>Tip:</strong> Write these down. Create a list you can revisit when doubt creeps
        in. The evidence for structural pain is often weak — bulging discs and "degeneration"
        are normal age-related findings in pain-free people.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section style="margin: 2rem 0;">
      <div style="display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 0.75rem; margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">
        <div style="background: var(--teal); color: white; border-radius: 50%; width: 36px; height: 36px; display: flex; align-items: center; justify-content: center; font-weight: 700;">3</div>
        <h3 style="margin: 0;">Somatic Tracking: the core technique</h3>
      </div>
      <p>
        This is where the real neural rewiring happens. Somatic tracking involves attending to
        pain sensations with <strong>curiosity and safety</strong> rather than fear and resistance.
      </p>

      <div class="card" style="margin: 1rem 0; border-left: 4px solid var(--teal);">
        <h4 style="margin-top: 0; font-size: 1rem;">How to do somatic tracking</h4>
        <ol style="margin-bottom: 0; line-height: 1.9;">
          <li><strong>Find the sensation.</strong> Notice where the pain is in your body. Don't resist it — acknowledge it.</li>
          <li><strong>Observe with curiosity.</strong> What does it actually feel like? Hot? Tight? Pulsing? Dull? Get descriptive, not judgmental. "Interesting — there's a tightness in my lower back that feels warm."</li>
          <li><strong>Send messages of safety.</strong> Tell your brain: "This sensation is safe. There is no danger. My body is okay. This is just my brain being overprotective." Say it genuinely — not as an empty mantra.</li>
          <li><strong>Don't try to make it go away.</strong> This is counterintuitive but critical. Trying to eliminate pain signals to the brain that pain is a threat. Instead, accept the sensation's presence while reinforcing safety. Paradoxically, this allows it to fade.</li>
          <li><strong>Shift attention gently.</strong> Gradually let your attention broaden — include the room around you, sounds, the feeling of breathing. Return to the sensation occasionally with the same curious, safe attitude.</li>
          <li><strong>Repeat.</strong> Practice this multiple times per day. Each time you face pain with safety instead of fear, the neural pathway weakens.</li>
        </ol>
      </div>

      <div class="card" style="background: #FFF7ED; border-color: #FDBA74; margin: 1rem 0;">
        <h4 style="margin-top: 0; font-size: 1rem;">Common mistakes</h4>
        <ul style="margin-bottom: 0;">
          <li><strong>Using somatic tracking to "fix" pain</strong> — the goal is to experience sensation safely, not to make it disappear. Paradoxically, this is what makes it disappear.</li>
          <li><strong>Getting frustrated when pain doesn't change</strong> — sometimes nothing happens in the moment. The rewiring happens over time.</li>
          <li><strong>Bracing against the sensation</strong> — tension and resistance tell the brain there's danger. Soften around the pain instead.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section style="margin: 2rem 0;">
      <div style="display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 0.75rem; margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">
        <div style="background: var(--teal); color: white; border-radius: 50%; width: 36px; height: 36px; display: flex; align-items: center; justify-content: center; font-weight: 700;">4</div>
        <h3 style="margin: 0;">Addressing emotional threats</h3>
      </div>
      <p>
        Pain often serves a protective function — it can distract from or express emotions
        that feel too threatening to face. Part of recovery involves addressing these
        underlying emotional drivers:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Identify patterns:</strong> When pain spikes, ask: "What was I feeling right before?" Anger? Sadness? Fear? Overwhelm? Self-criticism?</li>
        <li><strong>Allow and process:</strong> Give yourself permission to feel the emotion
        without judgment. Journal about it. Talk about it. Cry if you need to.</li>
        <li><strong>Challenge self-criticism:</strong> The inner critic is a major pain amplifier.
        Practice self-compassion — treating yourself the way you'd treat a friend.</li>
        <li><strong>Set boundaries:</strong> People-pleasing and over-giving create internal
        pressure. Learning to say no and prioritize your needs can directly reduce pain.</li>
        <li><strong>Process trauma:</strong> If there is a history of trauma, consider working
        with a trauma-informed PRT practitioner or EAET therapist.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section style="margin: 2rem 0;">
      <div style="display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 0.75rem; margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">
        <div style="background: var(--teal); color: white; border-radius: 50%; width: 36px; height: 36px; display: flex; align-items: center; justify-content: center; font-weight: 700;">5</div>
        <h3 style="margin: 0;">Gravitating toward positive feelings</h3>
      </div>
      <p>
        Your brain has been in threat mode — perhaps for years. Actively cultivating positive
        emotional states helps rebalance the nervous system:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Do things you enjoy</strong> — even (especially) when you don't feel like it.
        Joy sends safety signals to the brain.</li>
        <li><strong>Connect with people</strong> — social connection is one of the strongest
        antidotes to threat physiology.</li>
        <li><strong>Practice gratitude</strong> — not as toxic positivity, but as a genuine
        noticing of what's good alongside what's hard.</li>
        <li><strong>Engage in meaningful activity</strong> — purpose and meaning activate
        resilience circuits in the brain.</li>
        <li><strong>Move your body gently</strong> — as pain begins to shift, gradually
        reintroduce activities you've been avoiding. Start small.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <h2>What to expect during PRT recovery</h2>

    <p>
      Recovery is typically not linear. Here's what the process often looks like:
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>Weeks 1-2:</strong> Education phase. Learning about neuroplastic pain often
      brings immediate relief — your brain starts updating its danger assessment.</li>
      <li><strong>Weeks 2-4:</strong> Active rewiring. Daily somatic tracking practice. Pain
      may fluctuate — some days better, some worse. This is normal. The brain is testing
      whether it's safe to let go of the pain pattern.</li>
      <li><strong>Weeks 4-8:</strong> Consolidation. Pain often reduces significantly.
      Emotional processing deepens. Old triggers lose their power.</li>
      <li><strong>Months 2-6:</strong> Integration. The new neural patterns stabilize.
      Occasional pain flares are shorter and respond quickly to somatic tracking.</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="card" style="background: var(--teal-light); margin: 1.5rem 0;">
      <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 0.95rem;">
        <strong>When to seek help:</strong> While many people recover using Alan Gordon's book
        <em>The Way Out</em> or online resources, PRT is most effective with a trained practitioner.
        The <a href="https://www.painreprocessingtherapy.com/directory-of-practitioners" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        PRT practitioner directory</a> lists certified providers. Group workshops
        (<a href="https://www.painreprocessingtherapy.com/healing-workshop" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Healing Workshops</a>)
        are also available and more affordable than individual therapy.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div style="margin-top: 2rem; display: flex; gap: 1rem; flex-wrap: wrap;">
      <a href="/intro/treatments" class="btn btn-primary">All Treatments →</a>
      <a href="/protocols/schubiner" class="btn btn-outline">Schubiner's Method</a>
      <a href="/resources" class="btn btn-outline">Resources</a>
    </div>
  </article>
</Base>
